/*!
\page spec The SciLex contract — a formal specification

This page is the **contract** SciLex's lexer honours, stated precisely enough to depend on. It
describes only **delivered** behaviour (everything here ships in the current release); a feature that
is designed but not built appears, if at all, in a clearly marked *Planned* note, never in the contract
proper. The independent reference tokenizer in `fuzz/reference.hpp` encodes this same specification, and
the examples on this page are pinned executable against it and the real lexer (`tests/test_spec.cpp`),
so the prose here cannot drift from the code.

\tableofcontents

\section spec_tokens The token model and positions

A **token** is a typed slice of the source: a `kind` (a caller-defined `int`), a `lexeme` (a
`std::string_view` into the source bytes), a `start` \ref scilex::position, and the `mode_id` it was
lexed in. The lexer works on **UTF-8 bytes** — the source is a byte sequence, and a lexeme is a byte
range, never a re-encoded copy.

A \ref scilex::position is `{offset, line, column}`: `offset` is a 0-based **byte** index from the
start of the source; `line` is 1-based; `column` is 1-based and counted in the lexer's
\ref scilex::column_unit — **bytes** (the default), Unicode **codepoints**, or **utf16** code units.
The unit is chosen at construction and read back with \ref scilex::lexer::columns; a position does not
carry it. A newline (`\n`) increments the line and resets the column to 1, in every unit.

\section spec_munch Maximal munch and the tie-break

At each position the lexer considers the rules **active in the current mode** and picks a match by two
rules, in order:

1. **Longest wins** (maximal munch): among all rules that match at this position, the one with the
   longest match is chosen.
2. **Earliest rule breaks a tie**: on an equal match length, the rule that appears **earliest** in the
   rule list wins. So rule order is a tie-break only — put a keyword before the identifier rule that
   would otherwise match the same text.

A **zero-length** match never wins (see \ref spec_failures). The chosen token's `lexeme` is exactly the
matched bytes; the cursor advances by that many bytes, and lexing resumes at the next position.

\section spec_modes Modes — contextual lexing

A rule may be limited to named **modes** via its `in_mode` set (empty means the implicit `"default"`
mode only), and may carry a \ref scilex::mode_action that drives a per-scan **mode stack** when it wins:

- **push** enters a nested mode (remembering the mode beneath it),
- **pop** leaves the current mode, returning to the one beneath,
- **set** replaces the current mode in place (stack depth unchanged).

Only rules active in the mode at the top of the stack are tried. The same byte can therefore lex
differently by context — the canonical case is a Python f-string, where `{` opens an interpolation
inside a string body but a dict elsewhere; the stack top tells them apart. A mode may be marked
**insignificant** (Layout Awareness Level A): tokens lexed in it carry no layout structure, so code
spanning lines inside it is treated as continuation (see \ref spec_layout).

\section spec_skip Skip rules

A rule marked **skip** is matched and consumed like any other — it drives the maximal-munch decision
and any mode transition — but produces **no token**. Whitespace and comments are the usual skip rules.
A skip match still advances the cursor and updates line/column.

\section spec_eof End of input — eof_policy

\ref scilex::eof_policy chooses what the tokenizer does at the end of the input:

- \ref scilex::eof_policy::omit (the default) stops at the last real token.
- \ref scilex::eof_policy::append yields one final token of the reserved kind \ref scilex::end_of_input
  at the end position — the parser-friendly form, so a cursor always has a current token to match.

\section spec_failures The four failure modes and recovery

Four positions can fail to produce a token, listed first, then handled per the lexer's
\ref scilex::error_policy.

1. **No rule matches** (#1) at a byte.
2. **Zero-length match** (#4): a nullable rule matched the empty string and nothing longer — advancing
   by zero would spin, so it is an error.
3. **Pop at the root** (#2): a `pop` action while the mode stack is already at its root.
4. **Input ends inside a pushed mode** (#3): the source runs out while a mode is still open.

Under \ref scilex::error_policy::raise (the default), each raises a positioned \ref scilex::lex_error —
the historical behaviour, unchanged. Under \ref scilex::error_policy::token, the lexer **recovers**:

- **#1** becomes recovery: the maximal run of bytes that no rule in the current mode can begin is
  emitted as **one** token of the reserved kind \ref scilex::error (its `lexeme` the exact offending
  bytes), and lexing resumes — no exception, no mode transition (the run stays in its mode). The run
  ends at the first later position where a rule matches with positive length.
- **#3** yields one **zero-width** \ref scilex::error token at the end position, then unwinds to the
  root; any tokens already emitted stay.
- **#2** and **#4** stay **fatal** (they still raise) — recovery cannot make progress at them.

\section spec_layout Layout Awareness (Level A)

Over an \ref scilex::eof_policy::append token stream, \ref scilex::layout inserts the reserved kinds
\ref scilex::newline, \ref scilex::indent, and \ref scilex::dedent from each line's leading column,
turning an indentation-significant source into a layout-aware one. It is **mode-aware**: a token lexed
in an insignificant mode adds no layout structure, so a bracketed expression wrapped across lines is
**implicit line continuation** — no INDENT/DEDENT. An empty significance policy is byte-for-byte the
plain positional pass.

\section spec_reserved Reserved token kinds

SciLex reserves five kinds at the low end of the `int` range; user kinds must avoid them:
\ref scilex::end_of_input (`INT_MIN`), \ref scilex::newline, \ref scilex::indent, \ref scilex::dedent
(`INT_MIN+1..+3`), and \ref scilex::error (`INT_MIN+4`). They are mutually distinct by construction.

\section spec_linearity Inherited linearity

Every rule is a `real::regex` — a linear-time, ReDoS-safe engine. Because each position runs a
linear-time match and the cursor only advances, tokenization is **O(n·m)** in the input length `n` and
the program size `m` — linear in the input for *every* input, with no pathological cliff. The
recover-and-resync loop is bounded by the same guarantee; an unanchored, greedy rule that scans far
before failing pays that scan per position, which a first-byte prefilter mitigates.
*/
